VIII. This also is to be noted; that this Law of Nations respect- ing captives, has neither been received always, nor among all nations; although the Roman jurists speak universally, pointing at the more

¹ known part by the name of the whole. Thus among the Hebrews,

who were separated by special institutes from the common rules of other nations, there was a refuge for slaves (Deut. xxiii. 15): that is, as the commentators rightly note, for those who had fallen into that calamity by no fault of theirs. And from a like cause appears to have arisen the right which, in the Frankish land, was given slaves, of claim- ing to be free3 although at present that is given not only to captives taken in war, but to slaves of every kind.
